    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="233"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d233">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EAC/203</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 4278</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-08">July 8,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to your telegram no. 4844 of June 17, 1944, the Secretary of State
                    encloses herewith, for your information and guidance, a copy of a memorandum for
                    the President dated June 24, 1944, transmitting copies of two documents
                    regarding the treatment of Austria which had been cleared by the Department’s
                    Post-War Programs Committee. Copies of these documents, which are entitled “The
                    Treatment of Austria” (PWC–218), and “Summary: The Treatment of Austria: Policy
                    Recommendations” (PWC–217a) are likewise enclosed.<note n="62" xml:id="d233fn62">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_438">pp. 438</ref> and <ref
                            target="#pg_447">447</ref>, respectively.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Subject to the modifications which the memorandum pointed out will have to be
                    made, the President has now approved the two documents and they may be regarded
                    therefore as representing the present policy of this Government with respect to
                    Austria.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
